Illusionary Basics
By Mirhun Thinker, professor in the arts of Illusion

The purpose with the spells from the School of Illusion is to deceive the primary senses of others. They cause people to imagine or perceive things that are non-existent, not perceive things that are existent, hear, taste, smell and feel things that are not there and so on. Illusions come in five types: figments, glamers, patterns, phantasms and shadows, which I will describe in the following:

FIGMENTS:
Figments cover the area of spells that give false sensations. Figments are not, like some of the spells of illusion, subject to personal perception. The caster decides how the figment is in appearance and regarding sensory qualities. They do not make things seem like something else. Figments are not real, and do not regard anything substantial. As the figment is unreal, it cannot damage, move or change anything that is material. A figment can include sounds and intelligible speech, but such speech must be within the caster's comprehension. Thus it is not possible to make a figment that speaks elven, when the caster himself cannot speak elven. 

Examples of figment spells are: Silent Image, Illusionary Wall, Major Image

GLAMER:
Glamer spells are like figments; not real, and thus have no effect on matter than what the individual subject "decides" (i.e. it does not change the matter's true properties). A glamer spell veils a subjects sensory intrinsic worth, making it look, feel, taste, smell or sound like something else, or even seem to disappear. 

Examples of glamer spells are: Invisibility, Leomund's Trap, Magic Mouth.

PATTERN:
A pattern spell is much like a figment spell, in that it is visible for others to see. However, unlike the figment one can be affected by a pattern spell. Often it causes a confusion, disorientation or perhaps a form of fascination. Pattern spells only affect the mind. 

Examples of pattern spells are: Colour Spray, Rainbow Pattern, Hypnotic Pattern.

PHANTASM:
Phantasms are only mind affecting spells that can only be perceived by the caster and the subject, or subjects. Phantasms work only within the mental boundaries of the mind, which means that what is projected between caster and subject is not something fake that can be seen, but something that remains inside the mind, or within the mental bond that is created when said spells are cast. 

Examples of phantasm spells are: Nightmare, Phantasmal Killer, Dream.

SHADOW:
A shadow spell creates something that is partially real, or quasi real. The caster weaves it from extra-dimensional energies, like the ones that are drawn from the Shadow Plane. These illusions can have real effects. If a creature takes damage from a shadow illusion, that damage is real.

Examples of shadow spells are: Shadow Conjuration, Shadow Evocation, Project Image.
This was the most basic information regarding the School of Illusion. Of course, there are much more to be learned regarding how to cast mentioned spells, and what different hand patterns, finger movements and words of power there are.

One reality does not always spawn new realities. I do not like to use the word infinity much, since we cannot grasp at comprehending it, but because there, according to the Process of Decreasing Realities, is an innumerable amount of realities there are realities that are like ours in almost every sense. This is, of course, hypothetically speaking, and will all have reached a point soon. As explained before, it is theoretically possible to travel between what I call Third Layer Realities. Theory of Reality, Volume 1

Singular Reality String
Written by Mirhun Thinker, professor in the arts of illusions

We know that our reality, our universe or plane, is a place of its own. Intertwined with the planes of Shadow and Ether, we also know that we cannot reach the elemental planes through conventional means. This is all basic knowledge for any weaver. Travelling physically to one such place by just walking, flying or riding is impossible, since they do not lie as objects or places within our reality. Through this common knowledge, we know that there are other realities than our own. 

THESIS OF VARYING LAWS:
We're surrounded by rules and laws, defined by creation that cannot be broken. Some refer to these as the laws of nature, but since nature has been embodied in the form and thought of one or more celestial bodies, better known as gods, I will keep to the term "Laws of Creation", in order to separate religion and science. As I mentioned, these laws cannot be broken. Those that claim otherwise have obviously not seen the laws for what they are: indefinable by mortals. What we call "laws of nature" are but observations and theories based on probability, defined and supported by our own conceptions of calculation like mathematics. Note, that we near the indefinable laws by our observations and empiric methods, and should therefore not despair.

All this is true for every reality, ethereal and material alike. However one can conclude that different Laws of Creation are pertinent in different realities. The inhabitants of the plane of fire are aflame which the inhabitants of our world normally are not, and so on. So to come to the conclusion of this; different realities means different Laws of Creation. 

THE PROCESS OF DECREASING REALITIES
After having established the thesis of "Varying Laws" I can continue to describe our reality and what lies beyond. We can all agree that the gods created our world, but then who, or what for that matter, created the gods? The lord Ao? Then who created him? And what created the one who created lord Ao? This is a thought process that can be continued into eternity. We can hereby establish that there are an innumerable amount of creators. And for each creator that has been created, a new reality is put into existence. Because the created can never become greater than the creator, each new reality is necessarily less than that before. To simplify this, imagine each reality being a circle. Then imagine a circle within a circle, within a circle, within a circle and so on. This I call the "Process of Decreasing Reality" since each new circle becomes smaller, meaning that the Laws of Creation become more restricting and limited. Thus each reality is decreased, or lesser, compared to the former in which it lies. 

With all this in mind, I postulate that it is almost impossible to ascend through realities. We cannot even begin to comprehend our own reality, so how can we comprehend a reality greater than ours? We would mentally be unfit for this transcendent knowledge. In addition to the mental fact, there is a physiological fact that cannot be ignored either. In our reality, we are limited to four dimensions: the x-axe, the y-axe, the z-axe and time. There is a very good possibility that a reality greater than ours may have several more dimension. A possibility that I would go as far as to say is a fact. We were created to comply with the four dimensions that characterize our reality. So if there was to be fifth dimension we would be unable to exist, since we are not 'equipped' with that dimension. So theoretically we cannot ascend through realities.

The Unexplainable Void
Written by Mirhun Thinker, professor in the arts of illusions

Having established, or merely illuminated, several theories in the Singular Reality String, I can begin explaining what lies outside reality. In book one, we discoursed the theory of "The Process of Decreasing Reality", (a reality within a reality etc.), along with the "Thesis of Varying Laws" (different laws for different realities). I recommend that the reader refresh the memory of these concepts before moving on.

THE BEGINNING: 
In book one I said that reality would be expanding indefinitely and did not touch the subject of a beginning. Logically there must be a Supreme Reality, one infinitely large circle that encompasses all other realities. I'll call this one circle the "Supreme Reality" for later reference. What created this reality is the conundrum and paradox of this theory because, in order for it to be the first reality, nothing must have preceded it. The Unexplainable Void. Thus the "Primary Theory of Chaos" is defined: something created from nothing. It is illogical and will thus forever remain a thesis. 

A characteristic of the Unexplainable Void is; it resides outside of time, which is also a part of the paradox; that time is created from timelessness. The Void is indeed timeless since time is the main definitional point of all realities. Without time, nothing can exist out of the principal that there is no motion without time. The Void is also empty of everything, which perhaps makes it too hard to imagine since our minds think within the limits of the four dimensions. "The Primary Theory of Chaos", in its most general sense, is something coming from nothing.

THE SUPREME REALITY:
Something started reality, existence, something that is impossible for us to comprehend, and is thus irrelevant. However it is relevant to describe the Supreme Reality, because hypothetically encompasses all realities. It should hold an infinite amount of dimensions; it is the direct opposite of the Unexplainable Void, except that it too is impossible to define, since we don't have the capacity.    


 "The Primary Theory of Chaos" - something did come from nothing, but we can only grasp at how this happened. With this theory come the Supreme Reality and the duality of everything and nothing.

Theory of Reality, Volume 3

The Inevitable Conclusion
Written by Mirhun Thinker, professor in the arts of illusions

Through the courses of volume 1 and 2 on my theory of reality, I have explained a beginning and middle. But as the saying goes: "What goes up must come down, eventually."

THE END:
As we have theorised that there must be a beginning to reality, we can conclude that there must be an end. What starts, must stop. This will be known as "The Secondary Theory of Chaos", that everything becomes nothing. What will cause this end is unknown. Perhaps it is caused by realities finally reaching such a point where it simply cannot become smaller. Perhaps when/if it comes to a point where no more different realities can be created. A thesis could be that as long as realities expand, everything will exist, because the continuing dimension of time is indubitably connected to the movement of expansion. Something cannot expand, or exist as explained in volume 2, without time. So when the Process of Decreasing Realities stop, then time too will stop and with it all of existence. Of course, this is just one thesis. Another could be that, when no more realities can be created, then it will slowly retract itself and start going in an opposite motion of creation. Meaning, that all realities will implode slowly until the implosion reaches the Supreme Reality, where it will start over with expansion. A third thesis could be that when it comes to the point where no more realities can be created, nothing happens. No more realities are created, and life within the multitude of realities will go on as if nothing happened. 


As a conclusion to the three volumes regarding the Theory of Reality, there are some thing that I feel are necessary that be explained. This is a theory, though one shaped through logical thought, and should thus be regarded with some criticism. However people want to interpret the theories explained, is up to them. Truly we cannot know anything for sure concerning this reality, nor any reality, since properties expand with time. What might be a spoon today might be a deadly weapon tomorrow and so on. With each new discovery, the amount of properties an object can have increases. The same goes for thought on reality, since we with new innovations will come closer to the unreachable truth. Therefore, do not take these theories as facts, but use them to form your own theories. However, I will be working onwards with my trail of thought and more theories should be published soon.

Illusionary Basics
By Mirhun Thinker, professor in the arts of Illusion

The purpose with the spells from the School of Illusion is to deceive the primary senses of others. They cause people to imagine or perceive things that are non-existent, not perceive things that are existent, hear, taste, smell and feel things that are not there and so on. Illusions come in five types: figments, glamers, patterns, phantasms and shadows, which I will describe in the following:

FIGMENTS:
Figments cover the area of spells that give false sensations. Figments are not, like some of the spells of illusion, subject to personal perception. The caster decides how the figment is in appearance and regarding sensory qualities. They do not make things seem like something else. Figments are not real, and do not regard anything substantial. As the figment is unreal, it cannot damage, move or change anything that is material. A figment can include sounds and intelligible speech, but such speech must be within the caster's comprehension. Thus it is not possible to make a figment that speaks elven, when the caster himself cannot speak elven. 

Examples of figment spells are: Silent Image, Illusionary Wall, Major Image

GLAMER:
Glamer spells are like figments; not real, and thus have no effect on matter than what the individual subject "decides" (i.e. it does not change the matter's true properties). A glamer spell veils a subjects sensory intrinsic worth, making it look, feel, taste, smell or sound like something else, or even seem to disappear. 

Examples of glamer spells are: Invisibility, Leomund's Trap, Magic Mouth.

PATTERN:
A pattern spell is much like a figment spell, in that it is visible for others to see. However, unlike the figment one can be affected by a pattern spell. Often it causes a confusion, disorientation or perhaps a form of fascination. Pattern spells only affect the mind. 

Examples of pattern spells are: Colour Spray, Rainbow Pattern, Hypnotic Pattern.

PHANTASM:
Phantasms are only mind affecting spells that can only be perceived by the caster and the subject, or subjects. Phantasms work only within the mental boundaries of the mind, which means that what is projected between caster and subject is not something fake that can be seen, but something that remains inside the mind, or within the mental bond that is created when said spells are cast. 

Examples of phantasm spells are: Nightmare, Phantasmal Killer, Dream.

SHADOW:
A shadow spell creates something that is partially real, or quasi real. The caster weaves it from extra-dimensional energies, like the ones that are drawn from the Shadow Plane. These illusions can have real effects. If a creature takes damage from a shadow illusion, that damage is real.

Examples of shadow spells are: Shadow Conjuration, Shadow Evocation, Project Image.
This was the most basic information regarding the School of Illusion. Of course, there are much more to be learned regarding how to cast mentioned spells, and what different hand patterns, finger movements and words of power there are.

We're surrounded by rules and laws, defined by creation that cannot be broken. After having established the thesis of "Varying Laws" I can continue to describe our reality and what lies beyond. This is a thought process that can be continued into eternity. We can hereby establish that there are an innumerable amount of creators. And for each creator that has been created, a new reality is put into existence. Because the created can never become greater than the creator, each new reality is necessarily less than that before. To simplify this, imagine each reality being a circle. Then imagine a circle within a circle, within a circle, within a circle and so on. This I call the "Process of Decreasing Reality" since each new circle becomes smaller, meaning that the Laws of Creation become more restricting and limited. Thus each reality is decreased, or lesser, compared to the former in which it lies. 

With all this in mind, I postulate that it is almost impossible to ascend through realities. We cannot even begin to comprehend our own reality, so how can we comprehend a reality greater than ours? We would mentally be unfit for this transcendent knowledge. In addition to the mental fact, there is a physiological fact that cannot be ignored either. In our reality, we are limited to four dimensions: the x-axe, the y-axe, the z-axe and time. There is a very good possibility that a reality greater than ours may have several more dimension. A possibility that I would go as far as to say is a fact. We were created to comply with the four dimensions that characterize our reality. So if there was to be fifth dimension we would be unable to exist, since we are not 'equipped' with that dimension. So theoretically we cannot ascend through realities.

Through the courses of volume 1 and 2 on my theory of reality, I have explained a beginning and middle. But as the saying goes: "What goes up must come down, eventually."

THE END:
As we have theorised that there must be a beginning to reality, we can conclude that there must be an end. What starts, must stop. This will be known as "The Secondary Theory of Chaos", that everything becomes nothing. What will cause this end is unknown. Perhaps it is caused by realities finally reaching such a point where it simply cannot become smaller. Perhaps when/if it comes to a point where no more different realities can be created. A thesis could be that as long as realities expand, everything will exist, because the continuing dimension of time is indubitably connected to the movement of expansion. Something cannot expand, or exist as explained in volume 2, without time. So when the Process of Decreasing Realities stop, then time too will stop and with it all of existence. Of course, this is just one thesis. Another could be that, when no more realities can be created, then it will slowly retract itself and start going in an opposite motion of creation. Meaning, that all realities will implode slowly until the implosion reaches the Supreme Reality, where it will start over with expansion. A third thesis could be that when it comes to the point where no more realities can be created, nothing happens. No more realities are created, and life within the multitude of realities will go on as if nothing happened.

With each new discovery, the amount of properties an object can have increases. The same goes for thought on reality, since we with new innovations will come closer to the unreachable truth. Therefore, do not take these theories as facts, but use them to form your own theories. However, I will be working onwards with my trail of thought and more theories should be published soon.
